<br>
 Given this, is there a reason to think that drumming religion into kids heads before they're old enough to make up their own minds is child abuse? Brain washing?<br>
 You know that if a lesser known religion were doing it, the Xtians would be up in arms about the &quot;cult&quot; which is damaging kids. Because the cult is the major dominant religion, it's OK?<br>
<br>
 One of the silliest parts of this whole flap over the 9th court's decision, is the hysteria that stopping kids from being required to say &quot;under dog&quot; if they decide to recite the pledge, is somehow damaging the moral fiber of the nation. We need our belief in god right up front in order for our society to hold together.<br>
 Wrong in the basic premise anyway (You don't need religion in order to have moral or ethical lives, or to have purity of your purpose in life), and Again, they're <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>wrong in forcing a particular religion's views as the necessary way to instill virtue</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->.<br>
 I'm all in favor of having some class content in public schools about moral choices, ethical living, and spirituality.<br>
 The 10 commandmeents in schools? sure, but don't forget to include equal time for mentions fo other religions ethical teachings, as well as secular thought on philosophy &amp; ethics &amp; spirituality. (Heinlein's &quot;History &amp; Moral Philosophy&quot; courses, from the book &quot;Starship Troopers&quot; -and don't even think of the incredibly bad &amp; stupid movie)<br>
