Another, more common definition of Deism is contrary to being equated with Christianity, as a belief that the Creator then set things in motion to allow the universe and life, but then left things to their own accord; he/she/it doesn't step in and do miracles or judge individuals on belief or merits, etc. This is closer to pantheism, in that the will or mind of the creator is best known by examination and interrogation of the universe as it is. Revelation and prayer and salvation have nothing to do with any of it.<br>
<br>
I asked how much different writers who equated the founders of the Federal Constitution have examined the founders to see what evidence they may have left; If the inclusion of the nonspecific word &quot;creator&quot; in the Declaration of Independence is taken as evidence alongside the establishment clause in the first amendment (the only bit of legal writing there is; the declaraton is not a legal document of the US), it doesn't seem to go very far towards saying that they wanted the US to follow the Judeo-Christian Bible in it's make-up or laws.<br>
<br>
There is this, then<br>
quoted from Victor Stenger's book &quot;Has Science Found God?&quot;<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I almost shudder at the thought of alluding to the most fatal example of the abuses of grief which the history of mankind has preserved -the Cross. Consider what calamities that engine of grief has produced!<br>
John Adams -- Letter to Thomas Jefferson (undated)<br>
<br>
Millons of innocent men, women, and children, since the introduction of Christianity, have been burnt, tortured, fined, and imprisoned; yet we have advanced not one inch toward uniformity. What has been the effect of coercion? To make one half of the world fools and the other half hypocrites. To support roguery and error all over the Earth.<br>
Thomas Jefferson <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;Notes on the State of Virginia&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> 1781-1782, ed. Merril D. Peterson (New York Library of America, Literary Classics of the United States, 1984).<br>
<br>
Religious bondage shackles and debilitates the mind and unfits it for every noble enterprise... During fifteen centuris has the legal establishment of Christianity been on trial. What have been its fruits? More or less, in all places, pride and indolence in the clergy; ignorance and servility in the laity; in both, superstition, bigotry, and persecution.<br>
James Madison, letter to William Bradford Jr., April 1, 1774.<br>
<br>
The most detestable wickedness, the most horrid cruelties, and the greatest miseries that have afflicted the human race have had their origin in this thing called revelation or revealed religion. It has been the most destructive to the peace of man since man began to exist.<br>
Among the most detestable villians in history, you could not find one worse than Moses, who gave an order to butcher the boys, to massacre the mothers and then to rape the daughters. One of the most horrible atrocities found in the literature of any nation.<br>
I would not dishonor my Creator's name by attaching it to this filthy book.<br>
Thomas Paine, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;The Age of Reason&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, October 25, 1795.<br>
<br>
I have found Christian dogma unintelligible. Early in life I absented myself from Christian assemblies.<br>
Benjamin Franklin, in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;Toward the Mystery&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> (undated)<br>
<br>
&quot;The United States is in no way founded upon the Christian religion.&quot; --George Washington and John Adams, Diplomatic message to Malta<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Only Paine alluded to a personally held belief in a creator, and he adamantly distanced his belief from Christianity. None of the others said specifically that they do not believe in some form of creator, but they definitely don't seem to follow belief in a personally involved God -which is central to Christianity.<br>
<br>
Disregarding the Fundamentalist Christian apologeticists/revisionists of the XX century, the evidence seems to stack more towards the establishment clause as indeed preferring an interpretation of freedom <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>from</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> religion, as being at least equal to freedom <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>of</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> religion.<br>
Anybody with half a teacup's worth of common sense should see (and anybody with any integrity should admit) that the word &quot;God&quot; indicates Abrahamic monotheism, and in this culture, the connotation is Christianity.<br>
<br>
Keeping prayer and outright mention of adherence to Christianity or any other type of kind of religion out of schools most definitely does not impinge on anybody's rights to worship as they may choose, and doesn't say that the preferred status of citizens should be a-theism.<br>
 Teach the Constitution, and let people make up their own minds and do as they will -and don't force others to allow that your specific religious belief (or none at all) is the one and only correct way to think. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A> at: 12/2/03 5:54 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=aemann@nuclearspace>aemann</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/1/04 3:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=286.topic&index=37>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Good grief...</span><hr size=1> Is this really a thing? Here's the fact: There is no god. End of story. Get over it and move on. We're a bunch of animals scurrying round on the surface of an insignificant rock. If you think otherwise, you have a problem with your sense of perspective. Any reference to god or gods has no place in 21st Century. Absolutist? Yes. Guaranteed to inflame opinions? Yes. There is no god. End of chat. Opinion, Rights, historical blah blah blah... waste of electrons. Remove the reference, it is innapropriate and based on a falsehood - there is no god. Sorry christians, muslims, hindus, all believers in superior controlling powers - you got it wrong. There is no tooth fairy either. Or Santa. Its all made up. Invented by people. There is no god. Sorry to be the bearer of bad news, but you know it's true, if you're honest about it. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#6F6F6F>- </font><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace>NuclearSpace Message Board</a><font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com